   "source": [
    "## 9. The Pragmatic Listener (L1) with Flippy\n",
    "\n",
    "The **pragmatic listener** inverts the speaker model using Bayesian inference (Eq. 3, Eq. 11):\n",
    "\n",
    "$$L_1(w \\mid s, u, H) \\propto S_1(u \\mid w, s, H) \\cdot P(w)$$\n",
    "\n",
    "Given an utterance, L1 reasons: *\"If a rational speaker chose this utterance, what must the reward function be?\"*\n",
    "\n",
    "This is where flippy truly shines — we can express this as a natural probabilistic program using `draw_from` for the prior over worlds and `factor` for the speaker likelihood."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def make_pragmatic_listener_flippy(speaker, possible_rewards, utterances=None):\n",
    "    \"\"\"Create a pragmatic listener as a flippy probabilistic program.\n",
    "\n",
    "    The listener samples a possible reward world from the prior,\n",
    "    then weights it by how likely the speaker would have produced\n",
    "    the observed utterance under that world.\n",
    "\n",
    "    This directly implements Eq. 11:\n",
    "        L1(w | s, u, H) ~ S1(u | w, s, H) * P(w)\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    if utterances is None:\n",
    "        utterances = ALL_UTTERANCES\n",
    "\n",
    "    def pragmatic_listen(utt, context, horizon=1):\n",
    "        \"\"\"Infer the reward function given an observed utterance.\"\"\"\n",
    "        # sample a possible reward world from uniform prior\n",
    "        world_idx = draw_from(len(possible_rewards))\n",
    "        world = possible_rewards[world_idx]\n",
    "\n",
    "        # compute how likely the speaker would produce this utterance\n",
    "        # under the sampled world (this is the likelihood term)\n",
    "        speaker_prob = speaker.single_utterance_probability(\n",
    "            utt, context, horizon=horizon, reward_weights=world\n",
    "        )\n",
    "\n",
    "        # weight this world by the speaker likelihood\n",
    "        # factor() adds log-probability, so we use log of speaker probability\n",
    "        factor(math.log(speaker_prob + 1e-300))  # small epsilon to avoid log(0)\n",
    "\n",
    "        # return the world index -- flippy will give us a distribution over worlds\n",
    "        return world_idx\n",
    "\n",
    "    return pragmatic_listen\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"Pragmatic listener (flippy) factory defined.\")"
   ]
  },
